projectInfo.name: Mapping for WASH: N'Guigmi, Niger
projectInfo.shortDescription:
The OpenStreetMap Niger community is mapping the city of N'Guigmi, with support from HOT and CartONG, in order to help the NGOs who work in the city, including ICRC who will use the map for WASH projects.

`Contribution needed!`
projectInfo.description:
- Requesting Organization: **HOT, OSM Niger, ICRC and CartONG**
- Map Feature: `Buildings and highways

`Contribution needed!`

The Diffa area in Niger has been affected for years by the Boko Haram conflict. 

The OpenStreetMap Niger community with support from HOT launched in August 2017 this project to map  N'Guigmi, in order to help the NGOs who work in the city in their humanitarian activities as well as improve coordination.
In October 2017, the International Committee of the Red Cross and its partner CartONG joined the project. ICRC will use the data produced to plan water and sanitation activities with adapted, up-to-date maps.

Imagery: Through the MapGive project, the Humanitarian Information Unit (HIU) of the U.S. Department of State is providing the OpenStreetMap community access to updated satellite imagery services to help assist with humanitarian mapping.
projectInfo.instructions:
Imagery details
=======
This new imagery was taken by Digital Globe’s GeoEye-1 satellite on September 22nd 2017. It enables us to update the map of N'Guigmi  with the many new buildings constructed over the last years. 

**CAREFUL! imagery is not aligned properly, you need to adjust it so that it fits to the Bing imagery and existing data**

To do so:
* In ID:  press the "B" key to open the Background Settings menu, and unfold the "Adjust imagery offset" section on the bottom: adjust manually the imagery in order to fit the imagery with existing data (buildings, roads). Now you can start mapping !
* In JOSM: Open the menu Imagery/Preference imagery, click on the button "+TMS" on the bottom right hand corner. Copy and paste the imagery URL, enter the name "N'Guigmi" and validate. Then open the menu Imagery/Imagery offset and adjust manually in order to fit the imagery with existing data.

*Offset is not regular but you should have values around "-4, 0.75".*

Buildings
=======
* In the ID editor: label the area as “Building”, or "Huts" then correct for right angles with the “S” key

* In JOSM: from the Tags/Memberships window, click “Add” and use the tag *building=yes* or *building=hut*; then correct for right angles using the “Q” key

 DO NOT STICK OTHER BUILDINGS OR ROADS Do not hesitate to delete buildings that are not anymore existing.

It is also necessary to take into account the reflection of objects because some buildings have clay roofs, which makes their visibility blurred.

Road network
===========
Roads should be identified with respect to their economic and social role, not in terms of their visibility/viability.

*  **Inside the city** please use *highway=residential*  (with the exception of major roads) (in ID : choose "Residential road")

* **Outside of the city** please use *highway=unclassified* ("Minor routes" in ID) : for those roads connecting villages and hamlets, * *highway=track*  for roads or paths which connect *fields only*, and *highway=path* for roads too narrow for a 4-wheel drive vehicle to pass.

You shoudn't have to use :

* *highway=primary*, *highway=secondary* or *highway=tertiary* : these are the main roads that connect towns. You shouldn’t need to create them for this project.

The most important thing is to maintain consistency in the network. Every road should connect to another of greater importance and not to isolated roads.

See the Wiki page [Highway Africa Tag](http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Highway_Tag_Africa) for more information on the cartography of route networks in Africa.

Land use
===========
You can also trace appropriate land use areas (e.g. *natural=water*, *landuse=forest*, or *landuse=farmland* ).
